1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bf4 Bg7 8. Nd2 O-O 9. Nc4 Nh5 10. Qd2 $2 {A terrible mistake. White's dark-squared bishop is his most important piece and shouldn't be given up lightly. For the remaining game he will have a hard time defending this colour complex.} ({After all the previous moves, White had to go for the complicated} 10. Bxd6 Re8 {, which offers Black a dangerous lead in development and the initiative, but at least White gets some material in return and his important bishop is still alive.}) 10... Nxf4 11. Qxf4 Nd7 $17 12. e3 (12. Nxd6 $4 Be5) (12. Qxd6 {was possible, but Black has a huge initiative after} b5 13. Nxb5 Rb8) 12... Ne5 {Now White has nothing in return for the loss of his bishop (which in itself can be viewed as a material disadvantage) and Black's large lead in development.} 13. Rc1 ({Or} 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. Qa4 a6 ({Also good is} 14... f5) 15. Qc2 b5 16. a3 {Here Stockfish already gives Black an advantage of at least 3 pawns with almost any reasonable move.}) 13... f5 14. h4 {To prevent g6-g5.} a6 15. Be2 b5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 17. Qg5 Bf6 18. Qf4 Be5 19. Qg5 Bf6 20. Qf4 Ra7 21. g3 Re7 22. Bf3 Be5 23. Qg5 Kg7 {And on top of everything, White's queen is trapped.} 24. e4 f4 25. h5 Bf6 26. h6+ Kg8 0-1

