1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. d5 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bf4 a6 8. a4 Bg7 9. e3 O-O 10. Nd2 $2 Nh5 $17 {White has no compensation for the trade of his most valuable minor piece, the dark-squared bishop. This kind of trade is acceptable (for both sides) when Black has to weaken his kingside and his light squares with h7-h6 and g6-g5 in order to achieve it.} 11. Bg3 Nxg3 12. hxg3 Nd7 $1 {Anticipating 13.Nc4, which can now be met with 13...Ne5 or 13... Nb6.} ({For example} 12... Re8 $2 13. Nc4 {would have considerably slowed down Black's development.}) 13. Be2 Re8 14. Nc4 Ne5 15. Qb3 Nxc4 16. Qxc4 Qa5 17. O-O Bd7 18. Ra3 Bxc3 $2 {A strange decision. The arising endgame is still slightly better for Black, but it would have been much better to keep the pair of bishops on the board and make use of its dynamic potential.} ({For example} 18... h5 $17 {, with the idea to turn the attention to the kingside at an appropriate moment.}) 19. Qxc3 Qxc3 20. bxc3 b5 21. axb5 axb5 22. Rfa1 Rxa3 23. Rxa3 Rb8 24. Kf1 Kf8 25. Ke1 h5 26. Ra7 Ke8 27. Ra6 Ke7 28. e4 b4 29. Kd2 bxc3+ 30. Kxc3 Rb4 31. Bd3 f6 32. Ra7 Kd8 33. Ra8+ Ke7 34. f3 Ra4 35. Rb8 Ra3+ 36. Rb3 Rxb3+ 37. Kxb3 f5 38. Kc4 Kf6 39. f4 fxe4 40. Bxe4 Bf5 41. Bf3 Bb1 42. Kc3 Kf5 43. Kc4 Be4 44. Bd1 Bxg2 45. Bc2+ Be4 46. Bd1 h4 47. gxh4 Kxf4 48. h5 gxh5 49. Bxh5 Ke5 50. Bf7 Bb1 0-1

