{This game is an example of the dangers of early flank activity. As demonstrated by Banikas, White does not always have to prevent Black's queenside expansion with a2-a4.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 c5 4. d5 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nc3 a6 7. Bg2 b5 {Starting play on the flank is risky when White has the option to quickly strike in the centre.} (7... g6 {was safer, transposing into the regular lines of the g3-variation.}) 8. Nf3 g6 ({Pushing the knight away from the centre looks logical, but it also has its downsides:} 8... b4 9. Na4 {The pressure against c5 adds even more strenght to the e2-e4-e5 advance.} g6 (9... Be7 $5) 10. O-O Bg7 11. e4 {, and White has a strong initiative.}) 9. O-O Bg7 10. Bf4 ({Stronger was the immediate} 10. e4 O-O 11. e5 dxe5 12. Nxe5 $16 {White will continue with d5-d6 or Nc6 at a good moment, making good use of his strong d-pawn and fianchetto bishop.}) 10... O-O (10... b4 {was preferable, with the idea} 11. Na4 O-O 12. Nd2 Nh5 $132) 11. a3 $1 {Good prophylaxis. Now Black cannot play b5-b4 without ceding control of the d4-square anymore.} Re8 (11... Nh5 $144 12. Bg5 Qb6) 12. Re1 h6 13. e4 g5 $2 ({No better is} 13... b4 $2 14. axb4 cxb4 15. Nb5 Bf8 16. e5 dxe5 17. Bxe5 $18) (13... Bg4 $1 $132 {was correct, getting rid of the weakest minor piece and reducing White's control of the important e5-square.}) 14. Bxd6 $1 Qxd6 15. e5 Qd8 16. exf6 Rxe1+ 17. Qxe1 Bxf6 18. d6 Bb7 19. Rd1 Nd7 20. h4 Qf8 21. hxg5 hxg5 22. Nd5 Qxd6 23. Nf4 Qc7 24. Nh5 Bd4 25. Nxd4 cxd4 26. Bxb7 Qxb7 27. Qe7 Qd5 28. Qxd7 Qf3 29. Qg4 Qxg4 30. Nf6+ Kg7 31. Nxg4 f5 32. Ne5 Re8 33. Nc6 Re2 34. b4 Ra2 35. Rd3 1-0

