1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 d6 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 7. e4 a6 8. a4 Bg4 9. Be2 Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Nbd7 11. Bf4 Qe7 12. O-O Bg7 13. Re1 (13. e5 dxe5 14. d6 Qe6 15. Re1 O-O 16. Bxb7 Ra7 17. Bf3 Rb8 $13 {Black is threatening Rxb2 and Rb4-d4. White's bishop pair looks imposing, but his advanced d-pawn is weak rather than strong.}) 13... O-O 14. a5 ({Black should be flexible in his choice of plans. For example after} 14. Qd2 {, the protection of some light squares has been weakened and the prospect of a knight coming to b3 is unpleasant:} c4 $1 (14... Ne8 $6 {does not meet the demands of the position, which can be exploited by White with} 15. Bg4 $1 Ne5 16. Be2 $14 Nc7 17. Bg5 f6 (17... Bf6 18. Bh6 Rfe8 19. f4) 18. Be3) 15. Be2 Rac8 16. a5 Nc5 $132) 14... Ne8 {Now, with the b5-square available, this plan looks very logical.} 15. Qc2 (15. Qd2 {looks like the better square for the queen, for example} Nc7 16. Bg5 Bf6 (16... f6 $2 17. Be3 $16) 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 $13) 15... Nc7 16. Be2 Rab8 17. Bd2 Bd4 ({Also good is the immediate} 17... b5 18. axb6 Rxb6) 18. Bf1 Qf6 19. Be3 Rfe8 20. Bxd4 Qxd4 21. Ra4 Qf6 22. Raa1 b5 23. axb6 Rxb6 24. Ra2 Reb8 25. Rea1 Ne5 26. h3 (26. Nd1 $5 Nb5 27. Rxa6 (27. Bxb5 axb5 $15) 27... Rxa6 28. Rxa6 Nd4 {, with more than enough compensation for the pawn.}) 26... Rb4 27. Qd2 Nb5 (27... g5 $5) 28. Nxb5 axb5 29. Qc2 (29. f4 $2 {does not work for White:} Nc4 30. Bxc4 bxc4 31. e5 dxe5 32. d6 Qxf4 33. Qxf4 exf4 34. d7 Kf8) 29... Kg7 30. Kh1 h5 31. Re1 h4 32. Kg1 Qf4 33. Ra6 Rd4 34. Re3 g5 35. Be2 b4 36. Ra7 (36. Rxd6 Nd3 $1 (36... Nf3+ $2 37. Bxf3 Qxd6 38. e5 $16) 37. Bxd3 Qxd6 $17) 36... Rh8 $3 37. b3 Rh6 38. Bf1 g4 39. Qe2 gxh3 40. Rxh3 Rxe4 41. Qb2 Rd4 42. Ra2 Rg6 43. Qe2 Rxd5 44. Kh1 Rd4 45. Kg1 Qf5 46. Kh1 Re4 47. Qd2 Qxh3+ 48. gxh3 Nf3 49. Qb2+ Kh7 0-1

