1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 d6 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 7. e4 a6 8. h3 {Preventing Bg4 but at the same time allowing b7-b5.} b5 9. Bd3 Bg7 10. O-O O-O 11. a3 Re8 12. Re1 Nbd7 13. Bf4 Qb6 14. Qd2 {After strenghtening his position on the a1-h8 diagonal, White is now threatening b2-b4.} ({The immediate} 14. b4 Nh5 15. Bd2 {was possible, but Black has good counterplay after} Ne5 $132) 14... c4 $1 {An important move to secure the c5-square for a black knight.} (14... Bb7 $6 15. b4 $1 c4 $2 16. Bc2 $16 {The kind if position Black should avoid. His queenside majority is firmly blockaded and White has control of the d4-square and good prospects in the centre and on the kingside.}) 15. Bc2 Nc5 $5 {Very ambitious, preparing the bishop's development to d7 and taking no precautions against e4-e5.} (15... Bb7 {is the standard development. The bishop is passive for the moment but helps discourage White from pushing his e-pawn.}) 16. e5 {The consistent reply. Now the game becomes very sharp.} ({Also possible was} 16. Be3 Nfd7 17. Bd4 Ne5 $1 18. Nxe5 dxe5 19. Be3 Qd6 20. Rac1 Bd7 {, with a good position for Black. He can follow up a6-a5, b5-b4 and possibly transfer his knight to d6.}) ({Or} 16. Bh6 a5 $132) 16... dxe5 17. Bxe5 Bb7 18. Rad1 Rad8 19. Qf4 Nh5 20. Qh4 $6 Bxe5 21. Nxe5 $6 (21. Rxe5 $142) 21... Qf6 $1 22. Qd4 $6 {After yet another inaccurate move, White has serious problems. His pieces are somewhat unstable and the d-pawn is becoming a liability.} Nd7 23. Nc6 Rxe1+ 24. Rxe1 Bxc6 25. Qxf6 Ndxf6 $17 26. dxc6 Rc8 27. g4 Nf4 28. Kh2 Rxc6 29. g5 N6h5 30. Re8+ Kg7 31. h4 Rd6 $19 32. Ne4 Rd4 33. f3 Nd3 34. b4 Ne1 0-1

