{[%evp 0,30,19,31,14,-14,-11,0,28,50,45,45,76,68,117,73,68,65,59,43,39,59,68,63,64,53,49,63,49,36,33,30,44]} 1. d4 $5 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 d6 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 7. Qa4+ $5 {A rare move. This check aims to provoke Bd7 followed by Qb3 and disturb our natural development. That's why instead we go Ndb7!} Nbd7 $5 {all you need to know in the Qa4+ variation..is that you go Nbd7! intending a6!-Rb8! and b5!} 8. Bf4 (8. e4 $6 {Doesn't put any pressure on Black and we can continue developing naturally with Bg7 0-0} Bg7 9. Nb5 $2 {going after the pawn is too much} O-O 10. Nxd6 Nb6 $19) 8... a6 9. e4 (9. e3 Rb8 $1 $11 {Black has a good Benoni position} 10. Be2 b5 11. Qc2 {Black would like to play Bg7 but d6 is hanging, so either Qe7 first or Nb6} Qe7 (11... Nb6 12. e4 Bg7)) (9. Nb5 $2 Qb6) 9... Rb8 10. Bd3 (10. Qc2 b5 11. Be2 Qe7 12. O-O Bg7 13. a3 O-O 14. Nd2 Re8 $132) 10... b5 11. Qc2 Nh5 $5 {trying to kick away the bishop so we can develop with Bg7} (11... Qc7 12. O-O c4 13. Be2 Bg7 14. Nd4) (11... Qe7 12. O-O Ng4) 12. Bg5 (12. Bd2 {this move doesn't put any pressure on Black} Bg7 13. O-O O-O {Black is already better since he has played on all the sides of the board, especially on the queenside since he got the b5 push in}) 12... Be7 13. Bh6 Bf8 $5 {with a probable repetition} (13... Bf6 {might be a way to continue the game, but Bf8 seems to be best} 14. O-O Ng7) 14. Bxf8 Kxf8 15. O-O Kg7 $15 *

