{[%evp 0,101,14,29,33,12,39,33,61,61,61,61,61,68,108,77,79,81,90,77,63,54,49,40,38,31,32,6,2,-5,-3,-10,-15,-106,-17,-94,-73,-87,-113,-66,-107,-116,-70,-49,60,77,5,8,-22,-32,0,0,-11,-2,-26,-39,43,95,149,105,141,173,234,228,153,71,95,34,265,264,310,310,303,171,162,155,169,71,76,0,73,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,-77,185,208,166,171,171,171,167,180,180,150,278,268,360,417] the 7.Bg5 variation} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bg5 {here we go after the bishop} h6 $1 8. Bh4 g5 $1 9. Bg3 Nh5 {first we eliminate the bishop and then play Bg7} 10. e3 (10. e4 {is not as good as e3 because} Nxg3 11. hxg3 Bg7 12. Bd3 O-O 13. O-O Nd7 {White prefers to have the pawn on e3 and more dark-squared control since he is missing the bishop. Additionally, the Bd3 would have more scope over the light squares and the b1-h7 diagonal} (13... Bg4 {we don't want to play Bg4 as Bxf3 is not really a threat. If the pawn were on g6, we would have more control over the light squares, but now we need our bishop to watch over them} 14. Qc2)) 10... Nxg3 11. hxg3 Bg7 {This position was fashionable 40-50 years ago} 12. Bd3 O-O {[%cal Gf7f5,Gb8d7] next we want to go either f5 or Nd7} (12... Nd7 {is also possible but I would prefer to try and keep the light-squared bishop, since here White has} 13. Bf5 {[%csl Gf5] and eventually Black has to trade since the Bf5 is strong}) 13. Qc2 (13. O-O f5 {Black has a comfortable position}) (13. Nd2 Nd7 14. Nc4 {The usual way to meet Nc4 is either Ne5 or Nb6. Ne5 is not possible here because Nxe5 and on Bxe5, h6 will fall. That's why Nb6} (14. Bf5 {is possible but after} Ne5 {Black is doing very well}) 14... Nb6) 13... f5 $1 {Na6 was also possible} 14. Nd2 Na6 $1 15. a3 (15. Bxa6 {it's a very rare case in the Benoni for White to take the knight on a6} bxa6 {Black's position has some weaknesses but in return, it's full of dynamic potential, having the bishop pair, open diagonals and open lines, possibility to attack on either side of the board} 16. O-O {Black has many plans at his disposal} a5 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gc8a6,Ga8b8,Gb8b2,Ga6f1,Gg7b2] this one is focusing more on the queenside but there are other possibilities too, such as:} (16... Rb8 17. Nc4 Rb7 {[%cal Gb7f7,Ga8b8,Gb8b7] a rook transfer on the kingside to support kingside operations}) (16... g4 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Gc3e2,Ge2f4,Gh6h5,Gh5h4] even this is an idea with h5-h4 but it looks a bit premature since it gives away the f4 square as an outpost for the White knight, so maybe to improve it, Black can start with h5 first}) (16... h5 {with pushing the pawns g4 h4})) 15... Nc7 $1 $15 {Black has played a perfect game so far...memorize his moves!!} 16. f4 b5 17. Kf2 c4 18. Be2 Bb7 19. fxg5 hxg5 20. g4 Nxd5 (20... Qf6 $19) 21. Bf3 Nxc3 22. Bxb7 Rb8 23. Bf3 Ne4+ 24. Nxe4 fxe4 25. Qxe4 Qf6 26. Kg1 Rf7 27. a4 b4 28. Qxc4 Qxb2 29. Rf1 Kf8 30. Rh3 Qc3 31. Bd5 Rf6 32. Rhf3 Ke7 33. Qe4+ Qe5 34. Rxf6 Bxf6 35. Qh7+ Kd8 36. Qg8+ Kc7 37. Rc1+ Kd7 38. Qh7+ Be7 39. Bc6+ Ke6 40. Be4 d5 41. Qg6+ Bf6 42. Rc6+ Ke7 43. Bxd5 Qxe3+ 44. Kf1 Rf8 45. Re6+ Qxe6 46. Bxe6 Kxe6 47. Ke2 Rb8 48. Qf5+ Kf7 49. Qd7+ Be7 50. Qxa7 Rd8 51. Qb7 1-0

