{[%evp 0,96,14,6,35,12,4,13,16,22,58,55,71,62,109,80,83,72,72,72,54,31,35,45,23,24,40,16,26,11,-6,-20,-28,-31,-21,-44,-51,-110,-109,-112,-89,-81,-94,-114,-92,-127,-112,-94,-103,-120,-103,-95,-103,-118,-60,-39,-37,-37,-38,-120,-145,-145,-130,-121,-101,-123,-44,-52,-18,-18,-10,-30,0,0,10,-24,-18,0,22,23,158,0,140,170,170,39,39,-97,-26,-262,-248,-29991,-988,-29991,-29992,-29993,-29994,-29995,-29996]} 1. d4 {[%emt 0:00:02] In this game the move order is not important} Nf6 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 2. c4 {[%emt 0:00:01]} e6 {[%emt 0:00:00]} 3. Nf3 {[%emt 0:00:02]} c5 {[%emt 0:00:02]} 4. d5 {[%emt 0:00:02]} d6 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 5. Nc3 {[%emt 0:00:02]} exd5 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 6. cxd5 {[%emt 0:00:01]} g6 {[%emt 0:00:00]} 7. Bg5 {[%emt 0:00:03]} Bg7 {[%emt 0:00:02]} (7... h6 $1 {h6 is our move order since it's simpler. Also, Bg7 allows the additional possibility of e4}) 8. Nd2 {[%emt 0:00:04]} h6 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 9. Bh4 {[%emt 0:00:02]} g5 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 10. Bg3 {[%emt 0:00:01]} Nh5 {[%emt 0:00:00]} 11. e3 {[%emt 0:00:04]} Nxg3 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 12. hxg3 {[%emt 0:00:02] There are many ways to go both for White and Black, so theory is not that important, what's important is to know the typical positions and plans that can be played} O-O {[%emt 0:00:00]} (12... Qe7 13. Bb5+ Bd7 14. Bxd7+ Nxd7 15. O-O O-O 16. e4) (12... a6 13. a4 O-O (13... Nd7 14. Nc4 Ne5) 14. Nc4 Qc7 15. Bd3 Nd7 16. Qc2 Ne5 17. Ne4 (17. Nxe5 dxe5 18. Bf5 Bxf5 19. Qxf5 Qc8 20. Qxc8 Raxc8 21. g4) 17... Nxc4 18. Bxc4 f5) (12... Nd7 13. Nc4 Ne5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Bb5+ Kf8 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gb7b5] the king is pretty safe on f8, now a6 b5 is coming} (15... Bd7 {is okay and playable, but I would like to keep the light-squared bishop since our light squares are weaker since most of our pawns are on dark squares}) 16. a4 {[%cal Ga4b5,Ga7a6,Rb7b5] preventing a6 b5} a6 17. Bd3 Bd7 {Black has a comfortable position}) 13. Bd3 {[%emt 0:00:01]} f5 {[%emt 0:00:02][%cal Gb8d7]} 14. Rc1 {[%emt 0:00:05]} (14. O-O Nd7 {[%cal Gd7e5]} 15. Nc4 Ne5 (15... Nb6 {is another way to meet Nc4 and is also possible})) (14. Nc4 {now we are not in time to meet Nc4 with Ne5 or Nb6. One way is to go Qe7 but we need to be careful of Nb5, so instead, we can go Na6-Nc7} Na6 15. Nb5 Rf6 {defending d6, White spent a lot of time moving the same pieces in the opening, which can also backfire}) 14... Nd7 {[%emt 0:00:02]} 15. Bb1 {[%emt 0:00:02]} (15. Nc4 Nb6 {and Black is doing very well} 16. Nxb6 Qxb6) (15. a4 Ne5 16. Nc4 Nxc4 17. Bxc4 Bd7 18. Bb5 Bc8 19. O-O a6 20. Bc4 Bd7 21. e4 Bxc3 (21... f4 22. gxf4 gxf4 23. Re1 Be5 24. Qh5 Qf6 25. a5 Kh8 26. f3 Rg8 27. Re2 Rg5 28. Qh2 Rag8) 22. Rxc3 fxe4 23. Qh5) 15... Qe7 {[%emt 0:00:02]} 16. O-O {[%emt 0:00:02]} (16. Nc4 Ne5 17. Nxe5 Qxe5) 16... Ne5 {[%emt 0:00:03]} 17. Qc2 {[%emt 0:00:02]} Bd7 {[%emt 0:00:02]} 18. b3 {[%emt 0:00:02]} b5 {[%emt 0:00:02]} (18... f4 19. Qh7+) 19. Nf3 {[%emt 0:00:03]} Rae8 {[%emt 0:00:04]} 20. a4 {[%emt 0:00:04]} a6 {[%emt 0:00:02]} (20... b4 21. Nd1 a5 22. Nb2 Bc8 23. Nxe5 Qxe5 24. Nc4) 21. axb5 {[%emt 0:00:01]} axb5 {[%emt 0:00:00]} 22. Rfe1 {[%emt 0:00:01]} b4 {[%emt 0:00:02]} 23. Na4 {[%emt 0:00:09]} Bxa4 {[%emt 0:00:02]} 24. bxa4 {[%emt 0:00:02]} Nxf3+ {[%emt 0:00:02]} 25. gxf3 {[%emt 0:00:02]} Bc3 {[%emt 0:00:02]} 26. Red1 {[%emt 0:00:02]} c4 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 27. g4 {[%emt 0:00:06]} Rc8 {[%emt 0:00:02]} 28. gxf5 {[%emt 0:00:03]} Bf6 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 29. Ba2 {[%emt 0:00:24]} b3 {[%emt 0:00:02]} 30. Bxb3 {[%emt 0:00:01]} cxb3 {[%emt 0:00:00]} 31. Qxb3 {[%emt 0:00:01]} Qe5 {[%emt 0:00:03]} 32. Qd3 {[%emt 0:00:06]} h5 {[%emt 0:00:05]} 33. a5 {[%emt 0:00:02]} g4 {[%emt 0:00:04]} 34. f4 {[%emt 0:00:02]} Qb2 {[%emt 0:00:02]} 35. Rc6 {[%emt 0:00:04]} Ra8 {[%emt 0:00:08]} 36. a6 {[%emt 0:00:01]} Rfd8 {[%emt 0:00:08]} 37. Qe4 {[%emt 0:00:04]} Re8 {[%emt 0:00:03]} 38. Qd3 {[%emt 0:00:02]} Bh4 {[%emt 0:00:06]} 39. Rd2 {[%emt 0:00:02]} Qg7 {[%emt 0:00:07]} 40. Kg2 {[%emt 0:00:02]} Bf6 {[%emt 0:00:06]} 41. Rxd6 {[%emt 0:00:03]} h4 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 42. Re6 {[%emt 0: