{[%evp 0,80,48,22,22,0,0,10,29,21,25,35,108,105,105,71,107,52,58,36,43,45,59,54,60,70,70,24,40,41,38,11,30,13,57,39,25,25,21,12,21,-18,42,45,61,-6,-2,-1,-16,-5,-36,-30,-53,-49,-53,-88,-79,-85,-65,-79,-95,-95,-76,-76,-117,-124,-130,-116,-173,-246,-229,-276,-258,-399,-244,-299,-305,-323,-382,-474,-513,-823,-848]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 exd5 (4... d6) 5. cxd5 g6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Bf4 {the main line} a6 (7... Bg7 {a6 is much simpler, because on Bg7 White can play Qa4 which is an annoying check, since we don't have Nbd7 anymore because d6 would be hanging} 8. Qa4+ Bd7 9. Qb3 Qc7 10. e4) 8. a4 (8. e4 {on this both b5 and Bg4 are possible} b5 (8... Bg4)) 8... Bg7 9. h3 {it's important to start with h3! because this moves both Bg4 and Nh5} (9. e4 Bg4 10. Be2 Bxf3 {and this would go in the chapter with the pawn on e4}) (9. e3 {similar to e4, Black goes Bg4, takes the knight and there's typical Benoni play} Bg4 10. Be2 Bxf3 11. Bxf3 O-O 12. O-O Ne8 13. Qc2 Nd7 {[%cal Ga8b8,Gd8e7]}) 9... O-O 10. e3 Ne8 {we don't really need Qe7 here. From here on, there are numerous transpositions, so knowing the plans and ideas are much more important than knowing the exact theory. Black's ideas include Nd7, perhaps b6 to meet a5 with b5, ideas such as Ne5 and/or f5, preparing b5 with Rb8 and potentially Nc7} (10... Re8 {Here Ne4 is a possible idea} 11. Be2 Nbd7 12. Nd2 (12. Bxd6 {the pawn is not free} Qb6 {[%cal Gb6b2,Gb6d6]}) 12... Ne5 13. O-O Nfd7 {[%cal Gf7f5] this is how Black reroutes the knights} 14. Bg3 f5 {This is one setup with the knights - Ne5 and Nd7, but a much simpler setup would be with the knight on c7, which starts with 10...Ne8 instead of 10...Re8}) 11. Be2 b6 {[%cal Ra4a5,Yb6b5,Ga8a7,Ga7f7,Ga7g7] the idea is on White's a5 to go b5, Nd7 was of course also possible. With this, also the 7th rank is opened for a potential rook transfer in the future} (11... Nd7 {this is the basic idea}) 12. O-O Nd7 {not f5 as there can be Ng5 as the e6 square would be chronically weakened, so sometimes h6 g5 f5 can be an idea} 13. Bh2 (13. e4 Ne5 (13... Rb8) 14. Nxe5 dxe5 15. Be3 a5 16. Nb5 Bd7 17. Qd2 Bxb5 18. Bxb5 Nd6 19. f3 f5 20. Bc6 Rb8 (20... Ra7) 21. Qc2 fxe4 22. fxe4 Qh4) (13. Nd2 {whenever we see this move, we can jump in with} Ne5 14. Bg3 f5 {most likely after f4 from White we would put the knight on f7. We want to play g5 f4, but on our g5, White can respond with f4, so we need to be a bit careful. Another idea can include Nc7 Rb8 preparing the b5 push} 15. Qc2 Nc7) 13... Qe7 {to protect the d6 pawn, then Black can play Nc7 or even f5} (13... Ne5 {very rarely in the Benoni we allow this but here it's playable, our knight is coming to d6} 14. Nxe5 dxe5 15. e4 {because we wanted to go f5} (15. Qc2 f5) 15... Nd6 16. Qd2 Bd7 (16... f5) 17. Rfe1 a5 18. Nb5 Nxe4 (18... Bxb5 19. Bxb5)) (13... f5 $5 {with the bishop on f4 there was Ng5, here it's not possible} 14. Nd2 (14. e4 {is a bad move because it allows f4!} f4 15. Qc2 Ne5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 {[%cal Ga8a7,Ga7g7,Gg6g5,Gh7h5,Gg5g4] strategically winning for black, a rook lift on the 7th rank is possible}) (14. Bf4 {[%cal Gf3g5]} h6 {[%cal Gg6g5,Gh6g5]}) 14... Ne5 15. Re1 Rb8 16. Qc2 Nc7 17. Bf1 b5 $15) 14. Nd2 Rb8 15. Qc2 {now Nc7, Ne5, f5, all of them are possible} Nc7 16. e4 b5 (16... g5 {is another interesting move that would resemble the strategies with the pawn on e4, although we need to be careful of Nc4, the idea is taking more control over the e5 square and dark squares in general} 17. Nc4) 17. axb5 Nxb5 18. Nxb5 axb5 19. Ra7 f5 20. Bf3 f4 21. Bg4 Qd8 22. Bxd7 Bxd7 23. Nf3 Rf7 24. Rfa1 g5 25. R1a6 Be8 26. Rxf7 Bxf7 27. g3 Bh5 28. g4 Bxg4 29. hxg4 Qc8 30. Nxg5 Qxg4+ 31. Kf1 Qxg5 32. f3 Be5 33. Bg1 Qh5 34. Qf2 Kh8 35. Ra3 Qh3+ 36. Ke1 Bd4 37. Qh2 Qxh2 38. Bxh2 Bxb2 39. Ra7 Be5 40. Rf7 b4 0-1

