{an important game for the theory!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. d5 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bf4 a6 $1 8. a4 Bg7 9. h3 (9. e3 Bg4 {Bg4 again, White didn't play h3} 10. Be2 Bxf3 11. Bxf3 O-O 12. O-O Qe7 13. Re1 Nbd7 14. h3 Ne8 15. Qc2 Nc7) 9... O-O 10. e3 Ne8 11. Be2 b6 $5 {is an interesting idea, besides planning to meet a5 with b5, it's waiting for a White a bit, Nd2-Nc4 is a popular maneuver which can be a waste of time if Black meets it with Nd7-Ne5, in that case it would be better for White to spend those moves on something else such as 0-0} (11... Nd7 12. a5 Qe7 13. O-O Nc7) 12. Nd2 (12. a5 b5) (12. O-O Nd7 13. Nd2 (13. Qc2 Ne5 14. Nxe5) 13... Ne5 14. Qc2 Nc7 (14... f5 $1 15. Nc4 Nxc4 (15... Rb8 16. Nxe5 dxe5 17. Bh2 Nd6) 16. Bxc4 Nc7)) (12. O-O Nd7 13. Qc2 Ne5 14. Nxe5) 12... Nd7 13. Nc4 (13. g4 {this is not a good move because the White king has nowhere to go now, we should play actively in the center and on the queenside} Ne5 {[%cal Gf7f5,Gb6b5] ideas such as f5 or preparing b5} 14. h4) 13... Ne5 14. Nxe5 {White in fact lost 2 tempi on this manouevre! ...by going Nd2-Nc4-Nxe5! ...he could have take on e5 with a ...Nf3!} (14. Bxe5 Bxe5 $1 (14... dxe5 15. d6) 15. Nxe5 dxe5 16. O-O Nd6 {the knight can go to d6 first just in case, to avoid any d6 tricks and also it should go there anyway} 17. Bf3 {the idea is Ne4 to exchange our strong knight, so we need to prevent it} f5) 14... dxe5 15. Bg3 Nd6 16. O-O f5 $15 17. f4 e4 18. Qb3 Bd7 19. Ra3 b5 20. axb5 axb5 21. Rfa1 Rxa3 22. Rxa3 b4 23. Ra6 bxc3 24. Rxd6 cxb2 25. Qb7 Bc8 0-1

