{[%evp 0,82,19,18,51,-3,4,-11,45,50,62,62,62,59,114,68,101,59,71,34,38,29,43,34,41,59,41,33,45,27,27,-8,21,19,15,-6,-9,-9,-8,-5,-5,-18,-13,-18,-18,-15,-20,-18,-12,-49,-46,-66,-69,-60,-58,-72,-72,-72,-72,-63,-63,-63,-67,-84,-157,-129,-130,-130,-209,-209,-209,-209,-164,-195,-149,-150,0,-853,-886,-29995,-29996,-29997,-29998,-29999,473]} 1. d4 e6 2. c4 Nf6 3. Nc3 c5 4. d5 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bf4 a6 8. a4 Bg7 9. h3 O-O 10. e3 Re8 $5 {THAT'S THE OTHER AVAILABLE PLAN FOR BLACK.... INSTEAD OF PLAYING Ne8 ..and Nd7 -Ne5 and Nc7..etc etc...here he tries the plan with Nbd7-Ne5-Nfd7 .....in my view...the first plan with Ne8 is even better! .. I prefer Nc7 and Ne5, rather than Nd7 and Ne5} 11. Nd2 Nbd7 $5 12. Be2 (12. Nc4 {we have Ne4!} Ne4 13. Nxe4 Rxe4 14. Nxd6 (14. Bxd6 Rxc4 15. Bxc4 Nb6 {Black is winning material}) 14... Rxf4 15. exf4 Qe7+ {Black is winning material}) (12. Bxd6 {now there is no Qb6 since there is Nc4, but instead we have Nb6!} Nb6 (12... Qb6 $2 13. Nc4)) 12... Ne5 13. O-O Nfd7 14. Bg3 f5 {the downside of this setup with the knights on e5 and d7 is that the knights are fighting for the same e5 square and b5 is almost impossible to get in, in our system the knight goes to e8 and c7 supporting b5} 15. Qc2 (15. Nc4 $6 {is a bad positional move because it gives the d7 knight a job and frees up our position after the trade} Nxc4 16. Bxc4 Ne5 17. Be2 Bd7 18. Qc2 {perhaps planning some e4} Qf6 {White doesn't have e4 anymore because of f4. Black is doing very well}) 15... Qe7 16. Rfe1 b6 {White could have played a5 previously but hesitated, it was probably a good idea to play it earlier} 17. b3 Bb7 18. Nc4 Rf8 (18... Nxc4 {now Nxc4 is different since White has bxc4! opening up the b file to target b6 and strenghten d5} 19. bxc4) 19. Qd2 Rae8 20. Bxe5 Bxe5 (20... Nxe5 {Black can even consider sacrificing the pawn for the initiative} 21. Nxb6 g5) 21. Nxe5 Qxe5 22. Bc4 Re7 23. Rac1 Qf6 24. f4 Rfe8 25. Re2 (25. Qd3 Qh4 26. Bxa6 Bxa6 27. Qxa6 Rxe3) 25... Qh4 $1 $15 26. Rce1 Nf6 27. Qd3 Nh5 28. Nd1 Ng3 29. Rf2 Ne4 30. Rfe2 g5 31. Bxa6 Bxa6 32. Qxa6 g4 $1 $19 33. Nf2 Nxf2 34. Rxf2 gxh3 35. Ree2 Rxe3 36. gxh3 Qxh3 (36... Kf7 $1 $19) 37. Rg2+ Kf7 38. a5 Rxe2 39. Rxe2 Rg8+ 40. Kf2 Qg3+ 41. Kf1 Qh4 0-1

