1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 d6 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 7. h3 $5 {a clever move order for white! White wants to go e4. Very often we don't go Bg7 immediately, so we should think about it as what can White play and how do we reply} a6 $1 8. a4 {[%cal Ge2e4,Gf1d3]} (8. e4 b5) 8... Qe7 $1 {it is better not to allow e4!} (8... Bg7 $6 9. e4 $16) 9. Bf4 (9. Bg5 Nbd7 (9... h6 {is not the same now. The idea of h6 g5 Nh5 is to trap the bishop, but now with h3 it has the h2 escape square} 10. Bh4 g5 11. Bg3) 10. e3 Bg7 11. Be2 Ne5 $1 {in the Benoni, it is always good to exchange one minor piece!} 12. Nxe5 (12. Nd2 h6 13. Bh4 g5 14. Bg3 O-O 15. O-O Bf5 (15... Bd7)) 12... Qxe5 13. Bf4 Qe7 {losing one tempo like that to achieve our goal is worth it, Black has a comfortable position} 14. O-O O-O 15. Qc2 Nd7 (15... Nd7 {aiming to reach a very harmonious setup with Ne5 and Bd7} 16. Rfe1 Ne5 {[%cal Gc8d7]}) (15... Bd7 {may be playable but the knight can be improved from f6 first}) (15... Nh5 {is an interesting idea which resembles a game Spassky - Fischer Reykjavik 1972, where Fischer went Nh5 but it's not very good} 16. Bxh5 gxh5) 16. Rfe1 Ne5 17. Bg3 f5 18. a5 (18. Bf1 b6) 18... Bd7) 9... Nbd7 10. e3 Bg7 11. Bd3 O-O 12. O-O Nh5 (12... Ne8 {this is also fine, but we would have preferred to have the tempo and the queen on d8, in this line we went Qe7 earlier, so we also have another way to continue the game}) 13. Bh2 f5 14. Nd2 (14. e4 f4 {[%csl Gc5,Gd4,Gd6,Ge5,Gf4][%cal Gd7e5] with the same advantage on the dark squares and e5 outpost as usual when e4 f4 are played}) 14... Ne5 15. Nc4 f4 (15... Nxc4 {we must eliminate the knight! The knight is stronger than the Bd3, so that's why Nxc4} 16. Bxc4 Bd7 (16... Nf6 {[%cal Gf6d7,Gd7e5] is an idea})) 16. exf4 Nxc4 17. Bxc4 Nxf4 18. Rc1 Bd7 {Be5 can also look good but don't forget to develop the pieces!} 19. Ne2 g5 20. a5 Rae8 21. Nxf4 gxf4 22. Qf3 Be5 23. b3 Qd8 24. Ra1 Bxa1 25. Rxa1 Qf6 26. Rf1 Qe5 27. Bd3 Bb5 28. Bxb5 axb5 29. Qd3 Qe2 30. Qc3 Re5 31. Bxf4 Rxd5 32. Qg3+ Kf7 33. Bxd6 Rd8 34. Bf4 Rg8 35. Qc3 Qd3 36. Qc1 Qxh3 37. Bg3 Qh5 38. Re1 Re8 39. Rxe8 Kxe8 40. Qe3+ Kd7 41. f3 Rd1+ 42. Kf2 Qd5 43. Bf4 Rd3 44. Qe2 Rxb3 45. Bg5 Rd3 46. Qe7+ Kc6 47. Bf4 b4 48. Qc7+ Kb5 49. Qb6+ Ka4 50. a6 bxa6 51. Qxa6+ Kb3 52. Be3 c4 53. Qa1 Rd1 54. Qa7 h5 55. Qh7 c3 56. Qh6 c2 57. Qf4 Qc4 0-1

