1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 c5 4. d5 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Bg2 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. O-O a6 10. a4 Re8 11. Bf4 Nh5 $1 12. Bg5 Qc7 {A typical double-edged Benoni position has arisen.} ({Weakening the light squares with} 12... f6 $2 13. Bd2 f5 {leads to problems after} 14. Ng5 $16 {White's fianchetto bishop will become too active.}) (12... Nf6 $5 {looks like a loss of tempo, but White now has to prove that he has anything better than offering a repetition of moves with 13.Bf4. For example} 13. e4 Bg4 ({Black can also simply force the trade of White's bishop with} 13... h6) 14. h3 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Nbd7 16. Bg2 c4 {, with good play for Black.}) 13. Nd2 ({Also possible was} 13. Qd2 Nd7 14. h3 Rb8 {, with a good Benoni position for Black.}) 13... Nd7 ({An interesting alternative is the positional sacrifice} 13... h6 $5 14. Be3 Rxe3 $3 15. fxe3 Nd7 16. Nc4 Ne5 17. Nxe5 Bxe5 18. Qd2 Qe7 (18... Bd7 19. a5 Re8) 19. Rae1 Bd7 20. e4 Kg7 21. e3 Nf6 {, and Black has good compensation, with ideas like h6-h5-h4 or b7-b5. On the other hand, it's less easy to suggest an active plan for White.}) 14. Bf3 ({Pushing the e-pawn is premature:} 14. e4 Ne5 15. Qc2 h6 16. Be3 Ng4 {After this trade of pieces, only Black can be better, for example} 17. Nc4 Nxe3 18. Nxe3 Bd7 19. a5 Nf6 20. Rfe1 Bb5) 14... h6 15. Be3 Nhf6 (15... Rxe3 $5 {is an interesting option again.}) 16. Nc4 Ne5 {As a general rule, Black should immediately challenge a white knight on c4, either this way} ({or with} 16... Nb6) 17. Nxe5 Rxe5 18. Bf4 Re8 {Having exchanged a set of minor pieces without making any concessions along the way, Black can certainly be happy with the outcome of the opening.} 19. e4 ({Another possible line is} 19. Qc2 Ng4 20. Bg2 Ne5 {Now it is difficult for White to deal with this active knight, for example} 21. Bd2 Bd7 22. e4 {, and Black is already better after} c4 ({or} 22... b5)) 19... Nd7 20. Be3 (20. Qd2 {can be answered with} Ne5 ({or} 20... g5 21. Be3 Ne5 22. Be2 Bh3)) ({The attempt to prepare f2-f4 with} 20. Bg2 Ne5 21. Be3 {proves completely toothless after} c4) 20... Ne5 21. Be2 (21. Bg2 Bd7 22. a5 Nc4 $17) 21... Bh3 22. Re1 h5 $1 {Black clearly has the initiative, with active possibilities on both sides of the board.} 23. f3 Rab8 24. Rc1 (24. Qd2 b5 25. f4 Nc4 26. Bxc4 bxc4 $17) (24. a5 b5 $15) 24... Qd7 25. a5 b6 26. axb6 Rxb6 27. Rc2 Reb8 28. Qd2 Qb7 29. Rb1 Rb4 30. Nd1 Bd7 31. Nc3 a5 32. Ra1 a4 33. Ra2 Rd4 $3 34. Qc1 (34. Bxd4 cxd4 35. Nxa4 d3 $19) 34... Nd3 35. Bxd3 Rxd3 36. Kg2 Qb4 37. Bf4 Rb6 38. Ra3 Qa5 39. Ra2 Qa6 40. Ra3 Rb3 41. Ra2 Qc8 42. h4 Bh3+ 43. Kf2 Bd4+ 44. Ke2 Rxf3 45. Qh1 Qa6+ 46. Kd2 Qd3+ 0-1

