{This part will be mostly on Symmetrical English, which is an important part of a complete Benoni repertoire.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 {After c5, White doesn't have to push d5 and enter a Benoni} 4. g3 {You need to know what you are doing here with Black. Otherwise, you can end up in a worse position} (4. e3 {Now Black has 2 options, d5 or cxd4 and d5} d5 {Most likely we will end up with an isolated pawn} (4... cxd4 5. exd4 d5 {This will likely give White an isolated pawn} 6. Nc3 Bb4 {Be7 was also a possibility, Bb4 is more active}) 5. Nc3 a6 {[%cal Gd5c4,Gb7b5]} 6. cxd5 exd5 7. dxc5 Bxc5) (4. Nc3 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4 {Transposing to some variations of the Nimzo-Indian. Black is doing well.}) 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 {Now the best move for Black is d5! We shouldn't allow White to develop the pieces easily because if White does that, White will be better, so we should pose White problems as soon as possible. This is because after Bg2, the bishop is extremely strong, but at the moment, there is a lack of harmony between the White pieces and that should be used right now!} d5 ({If} 5... Be7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nc6 8. Nc3 {Black is in a passive situation and lacking constructive moves}) (5... Nc6 6. Bg2 Bc5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Nc3 d6 10. Bf4 {We end up in a passive position again} e5 $6 {Is not really good because it gives up control over d5} 11. Bg5 Be6 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. Nd5 $14) *

