1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 {Is the correct move order} ({If} 2... c5 3. d5 e6 {White can choose whether to play c4 or simply play Nc3 which is an additional line and possibly a better one for White} 4. Nc3 (4. c4)) 3. c4 c5 4. d5 d6 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 7. Bf4 a6 {The best move for Black} 8. e4 {Now Black needs to make a choice how to continue} b5 (8... Bg4 9. Be2 Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Nbd7 {This will not be the same position as White is not forced to play a4, although it's likely that a4 will be the reply that you will meet in practice most often. White can choose to completely omit a4} 11. O-O (11. a4 Qe7 {[%cal Gf8g7,Ge8g8] And this leads to the normal position with Bg7 and 0-0}) 11... b5 {[%cal Gf1e1,Ge4e5] Is dangerous with the king still in the center, Re1 and e5 may come quickly} (11... Qe7 {Is an interesting try, not going for b5 and hoping that White will prevent it with a4, which transposes to a comfortable position for Black after Bg7 and 0-0. Even though in practice, most often you won't encounter much resistance from White in this line (for example, White going a4), here White also has some attacking possibilities, that's why the main line is b5}) 12. Re1) 9. Qe2 {A strange move but a very venomous one if Black doesn't know how to deal with it. It supports e5 and prepares 0-0-0. Here, the most natural move Bg7 is a blunder because of Bxd6! Qxd6 and e5!} Be7 (9... Bg7 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. e5 $18) 10. O-O-O (10. e5 {Black is at least equal at the end of this e5 line} dxe5 11. Bxe5 {There may be some d6 ideas for White} Nbd7 $1 12. d6 $2 Nxe5 $19) (10. Qc2 {White forced us to play Be7, but also lost a tempo with Qe2-Qc2 and allowed us to gain space on the queenside} O-O {[%cal Gf8e8,Ge7f8,Gf8g7] This is how we achieve harmony between our pieces - Re8, Bf8, Bg7} 11. Be2 Re8 12. a4 b4 13. Nb1 {The idea is Nb1-Nd2-Nc4 taking the outpost} b3 $1 {[%cal Rc2b3,Gf6e4] Distracting the queen from protection of the e4 pawn} 14. Qc4 (14. Qxb3 Nxe4) 14... Nbd7 15. Nc3 Rb8 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gb8b4]}) 10... O-O 11. h3 {White needs to do something quickly or Black will have a tremendous attack against the White king, h3 is a bit slow} Re8 {[%csl Re2][%cal Ge8e2]} 12. Qc2 {The queen was feeling uncomfortable on the e-file against the Re8} Bf8 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gb5b4,Gb4c3]} 13. e5 {Black was already much better but now White loses a piece} (13. Bd3 c4 14. Be2 b4 15. Na4 Rxe4 $19 {is best, although we also can also consider moves such as c3 or b3}) 13... dxe5 14. Nxe5 (14. Bxe5 Nbd7 $19) 14... Bd6 $19 15. Nd3 c4 {[%csl Rd3,Rf4]} 16. Bxd6 cxd3 (16... Qxd6 {Even if Black didn't win a piece by force, this is just to show how good the Black position is} 17. Ne1 Bf5 18. Qd2 b4 $19) 0-1

