{[%evp 0,40,24,20,24,24,24,18,25,1,-1,-4,-1,-1,2,2,2,2,2,2,-5,-11,-11,-11,5,-11,-9,-30,7,-31,-34,-13,-52,-68,-69,-283,0,20,20,-252,74,83,50]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 (3. g3 c5 {Is our move order}) 3... c5 4. g3 cxd4 5. Nxd4 d5 $1 6. Bg2 {The only good move for White. Now again, Black needs to play actively!} (6. cxd5 $2 Qxd5 $1 7. f3 {[%cal Ge2e4,Gb1c3] White wants to play Nc3 or e4 but he is not on time} e5 8. Nc2 Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 Nc6 $17) 6... e5 $1 {our next move is d4} 7. Nf3 (7. Nc2 {Used to be playable, but the engines showed there is a problem with Nc2} d4 8. O-O (8. f4 {Tries to break down Black's center, but today's engines are merciless} Nc6 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. fxe5 Qa5+ 11. Qd2 Qxe5 12. Qxd4 {And they found this strong move} Qf5 $1 13. Ne3 Qh5 $17 {[%cal Gf8c5]}) 8... Nc6 9. Bg5 $6 Be7 10. Nd2 O-O $15) 7... d4 8. O-O (8. Nxe5 $4 Qa5+ {[%cal Ga5e1,Ga5e5]}) 8... Nc6 {The position is open and very active, but strangely enough, Black doesn't need to memorize a lot.} 9. e3 $1 {White must break the center immediately. If White goes for some quiet piece play, he will be worse immediately!} (9. Bg5 $2 {White can't afford the time to play moves like these since we will develop and castle} Be7 10. Nbd2 O-O {White can't set up a blockade on e4 after Bxf6 Bxf6 Ne4 since the bishop will return to e7 and f5 e4 will come next} 11. Ne1 h6 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 $17) (9. Nfd2 $2 Be7 10. a3 a5 11. b3 O-O $17) 9... Be7 $1 {There are plenty of games with Bc5 or d3, but the theory has advanced and the best move is Be7!} 10. exd4 {This is the initial position of the Symmetrical English! We have a passed pawn and it can be dangerous for White. YOU DON'T NEED TO MEMORIZE MUCH HERE! ... JUST STUDY THE SAMPLE LINES WHERE BLACK IS OFTEN BETTER! ...AND LEARN THE TYPICAL IDEAS! ...The most important one is that when White threatens Ne5, I go Be6! so that after Ne5 I can play Rc8!} exd4 {Here we shouldn't remember the variations, the ideas are important and if we want to memorize anything, it can be only our next move on whatever White plays - for example on a3 a5, on Re1 threatening Ne5 - Be6 in order to meet Ne5 with Rc8, on Qb3 Nd7 with the idea Nc5 and so on.} 11. Bf4 (11. a3 a5 {A simple way to play on a3} 12. b3 O-O 13. Bb2 {Here, I don't want to play d3 yet since there will be Nc3} Bc5 14. Qd3 (14. Nbd2 {Concrete moves don't matter here, we need to know the ideas with Black, Bf5, Bg4, Re8, all are possible moves} Bf5 (14... Re8 15. Re1 Bg4) 15. Re1 (15. Nh4 Bg4 {Provoking some disharmony between the White pieces} 16. Bf3 Be6 {The White bishop is not standing well on f3} 17. Ne4 Be7 18. Nxf6+ Bxf6 $15 {Black has a good play with the passed pawn}) 15... d3 16. h3 Qd6 {Both moves seem possible} (16... Qb6 17. Rf1 Rad8 $17) 17. Ne5 Nd4 18. Ndf3 Ne2+ 19. Kh2 Rfe8 $19 20. Nh4 $2 Rxe5 21. f4 Ree8 22. Nxf5 Qd7 23. g4 Nxf4 24. Qd2 Qc7 25. Bxf6 gxf6 26. Kh1 Re2 27. Qc3 Qe5 28. Qxe5 fxe5 29. Bf3 Rxe1+ 30. Rxe1 f6 31. Rd1 Nxh3 32. Kg2 Nf4+ 33. Kf1 Bxa3 34. Ne3 a4 35. bxa4 Rxa4 36. Ra1 b6 37. Nd5 Nxd5 38. Bxd5+ Kg7 39. Rd1 Bc5 40. Rxd3 Ra1+ 41. Kg2 Rg1+ 42. Kf3 Kg6 43. Be6 h5 44. gxh5+ Kxh5 45. Rd8 Rf1+ 46. Kg2 Rf2+ 47. Kg3 f5 48. Rd5 f4+ 49. Kh3 Rf3+ 50. Kg2 Rg3+ 51. Kf1 Re3 52. Rd8 e4 53. Bd5 Rf3+ 54. Ke1 Re3+ 55. Kf1 Kg4 56. Rh8 Bb4 57. Be6+ Kg5 58. Rg8+ Kf6 59. Bd5 Ke5 60. Rg5+ Kd4 61. Rf5 f3 62. Be6 Re1+ 63. Kf2 Re2+ 64. Kf1 Ke3 {0-1 Karner,C (2356)-Kuljasevic,D (2502)/Pula 2008/CBM 125 Extra}) 14... Qb6 (14... Re8 $1 15. Rd1 Bg4 $17 16. Nbd2 Qd7 17. h3 Bf5 18. Qf1 Bc2 (18... d3 19. Bxf6 gxf6 20. Nh4 Nd4 21. Nxf5 Ne2+ 22. Kh2 Qxf5 23. Bxb7 Rad8 24. Bd5 Rxd5 25. cxd5 Qxd5) (18... h6 19. b4 axb4 20. Nb3) 19. Re1 d3 20. Bxf6 gxf6) (14... Bg4 15. Nbd2 Qd7 16. Ne4 Nxe4 17. Qxe4 Rad8 18. Ne5 Nxe5 19. Qxe5 b6 20. Bd5 Rfe8 21. Qf4 Be6 (21... Be2 22. Rfe1 d3 23. Qg5 Bf8 24. Bf6 Rc8) 22. b4 Bxd5 23. cxd5 Bd6 24. Qxd4 Be5 25. Qd2 Qxd5 26. Qxd5 Rxd5 27. Rae1 Kf8 28. Bxe5 Rexe5 29. Rxe5 Rxe5 30. bxa5 Rxa5 {1/2-1/2 Gouloutis,N (1946)-Papakonstantinou,D (1858)/PATRAS 2012}) 15. Re1 Bg4 16. Nbd2 Bh5 (16... Rfe8) 17. Ne5 Nxe5 18. Rxe5 Bg6 19. Qf3 Qd6 20. Ree1 Rab8 21. h3 b6 22. Qc6 Qd8 23. Rad1 Rc8 24. Qb5 Bc2 25. Rc1 Bf5 26. Red1 Re8 27. b4 Bd7 28. Qa6 axb4 29. axb4 Bxb4 30. Bxd4 b5 31. Bxf6 gxf6 32. Ne4 Re6 33. Qb7 Rc7 34. Qd5 bxc4 35. Rxc4 Rxc4 36. Qxc4 Qe7 37. Rxd7 Qxd7 38. Qxb4 Ra6 39. Kh2 Qd1 40. Qb5 Ra1 41. Nxf6+ Kh8 42. h4 Qg1+ 43. Kh3 Qxf2 44. Qg5 {1-0 Galopoulos, N (2327)-Papathanasiou,E (1884)/1st Open Isthmia 2011}) (11. Nbd2 O-O $5 {Be6 was also possible} (11... Be6 12. Ng5 Bg4 13. Bf3 Bxf3 14. Ngxf3 O-O $15) 12. Nb3 d3 13. Bf4 (13. Be3 Be6 14. Rc1 (14. Nbd2 $17 {Black has several good moves, for example, Qd7 or Ng4} Qd7 (14... Ng4 15. Bf4 g5 $19)) 14... Bg4 15. h3 Bh5 16. g4 Bg6 17. Nbd4 Nxd4 18. Bxd4 h5 19. g5 Ne4 20. h4 Re8 21. Qb3 Bc5 22. Bxc5 Nxc5 23. Qa3 Qc7 24. Rcd1 Rad8 25. b4 Ne6 26. Qxa7 Ra8 27. Qe3 Nf4 28. Qc5 Qxc5 29. bxc5 Rxa2 30. Rd2 Rc2 31. Rfd1 Rxc4 32. Ne1 Re7 33. Bf1 Ne2+ 34. Bxe2 dxe2 35. Ra1 Rg4+ 36. Kh2 Rxh4+ 37. Kg3 Rg4+ 38. Kh2 Re8 39. Raa2 Rxg5 40. Rxe2 Rxe2 41. Rxe2 Rxc5 42. Re8+ Kh7 43. Rb8 Be4 44. f3 Rc1 {[%emt 0:00:02] 0-1 Radosevic,N (2203) -Antic,D (2484)/Belgrade 2014/Mega2015 Update}) 13... Bf5 14. h3 (14. Ne5 Nxe5 (14... Rc8 $5 15. Nxc6 bxc6) 15. Bxe5 Qd7 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Nc5 Qd4 18. Nxb7 d2) 14... a5 (14... h6) (14... Re8) (14... Rc8) 15. g4 Be6 16. Rc1 a4 17. Nbd2 a3 18. Rb1 Nd7 19. bxa3 Nc5 20. Be3 Rxa3 21. Bxc5 Bxc5 22. Rxb7 Rxa2 23. Qb1 Rc2 24. Nb3 Be7 25. Ne1 Rxc4 26. Qxd3 Bf6 27. Qb1 Rc3 28. Nc2 Qd3 29. Nca1 Ne5 30. Qxd3 Nxd3 31. Nd2 Bd4 32. Nab3 Be5 33. Na5 Nf4 34. Nc6 Nxg2 35. Nxe5 Nf4 36. Ne4 Rxh3 37. f3 Bd5 38. Rb4 Bxe4 39. Rxe4 g5 40. Nd7 Rd8 41. Nf6+ Kg7 42. Ne8+ Kf8 43. Nf6 Rh6 44. Rxf4 gxf4 45. Nh5 Rd4 46. Rb1 Re6 47. Rb8+ Re8 48. Rxe8+ Kxe8 49. Nf6+ Ke7 50. Nxh7 f6 51. g5 fxg5 52. Nxg5 Kf6 53. Nh3 Ke5 54. Kf2 Rd2+ 55. Ke1 Rh2 56. Nf2 Kd4 57. Ng4 Ra2 58. Kf1 Kd3 59. Ke1 Re2+ 60. Kf1 Kd2 61. Kg1 Ke1 {0-1 Przedmojski,R (2378)-Gritsak,O (2548)/Warsaw 2011/CBM 145 Extra}) (11. Qb3 $6 Nd7 $1 {The best move, going for Nc5} (11... Ne4 $1 $36) 12. Nbd2 O-O 13. Qd1 d3 (13... Nc5 {is another good move} 14. Nb3 Nxb3 15. axb3 Bf5 16. Ne1 Qd7 17. Nd3 $17 {This is an unhealthy blockade since the knight on d3 is already under pressure. That's why Bh3 would be a mistake. At some point, Black can even take on d3 and play Nb4 if needed.}) 14. a3 a5 $15) (11. b3 $6 O-O 12. Bb2 Bc5 {Defends the pawn} 13. a3 a5 {Prevents b4} 14. Nbd2 Bf5 $15) (11. b4 $5 {Is a move that we need to memorize a bit} Nxb4 12. Nxd4 O-O 13. Bb2 (13. a3 Bg4 14. Qd2 Nc6 $132 {Usually, in such cases, White will take the pawn. Black in return, will have very active pieces and compensation, so c4 will fall and it can turn out to be a drawish endgame.}) 13... Bg4 14. Qd2 Qd7 $132) (11. Re1 Be6 $1 {We should remember the idea that we want to meet Ne5 with Rc8!} 12. Nbd2 O-O 13. a3 a5 $15 14. Nb3 Qb6 $3 15. Nbxd4 Nxd4 16. Nxd4 Rfd8 17. Be3 Bc5 18. Qb3 Rxd4 $15) 11... Be6 $1 {White prepared Ne5, so Be6! first, we want to remove the rook from a8 from the dangerous diagonal} 12. Ne5 (12. Nbd2 O-O 13. Ne5 $2 {there's a combination here for Black} (13. a3 Nh5 (13... Nd7 $1 14. h4 (14. b4 g5) 14... Nc5 $15 15. b4 Nd3) 14. Nxd4 Nxf4 15. Nxc6 bxc6 16. gxf4 Qd4 $17) (13. h3 Qd7 14. Ng5 Bf5 15. g4 Bg6 16. Nge4 Nxe4 17. Nxe4 Rad8 $17 (17... d3 18. Nc3 Nd4 $17)) 13... Nxe5 14. Bxe5 Ng4 15. Bf4 (15. Re1 Nxe5 16. Rxe5 Qc7 $15 {Attacking the rook and planning to play Rfd5, this prevents all Bd5 ideas from White} (16... Bf6 17. Rxe6 fxe6 18. Bxb7 Rb8 (18... d3 19. Bxa8 Qxa8) 19. Nb3 Ra8 20. Nc1 Rc8 21. Nd3 Rb8 22. Be4)) 15... g5 {The bishop is trapped} 16. h3 gxf4 17. hxg4 fxg3 18. fxg3 d3 $1 $19 {Opening the diagonal towards the White king} 19. Bxb7 $4 Qb6+ ({Even if we had to play like this, Black still has a winning advantage} 19... Rb8 20. Bf3 Qd4+ 21. Kh1 Rxb2)) 12... Rc8 $1 13. Qa4 (13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Be5 c5 $1 (14... d3 $1 15. Nd2 O-O 16. Re1 Qb6 $132 (16... Qd7 $132)) 15. Bb7 Bxc4 $3 16. Bxf6 (16. Qa4+ Qd7 17. Qxd7+ (17. Qxc4 Qxb7 $19) 17... Nxd7 18. Bxc8 Nxe5 $17) 16... Bxf6 17. Re1+ Be6 18. Bxc8 Qxc8 19. Nd2 O-O $15) (13. Re1 O-O 14. Nd2 Nxe5 15. Bxe5 Qd7 $15 {[%cal Gd4d3] d3 will be played at some point}) (13. Nd2 Nxe5 14. Bxe5 Ng4 15. Bf4 g5 16. Re1 O-O 17. Be5 Rc5 18. Nf3 Nxe5 19. Nxe5 d3 20. Nxd3 Rxc4 21. Re3 Rd4 22. Qf3 b6 23. Ne5 g4 24. Qe2 Rd2 25. Qe1 Bf6 26. Re2 Rxe2 27. Qxe2 Qd4 28. Nc6 Qxb2 29. Qxb2 Bxb2 30. Rb1 Ba3 31. Nxa7 Bc5 32. Nc6 Bxa2 33. Rd1 Re8 34. Bd5 Re2 35. Bxa2 Rxa2 36. Nd4 h5 37. Kf1 b5 38. Ne2 b4 39. Rd8+ Kh7 40. Rc8 Ba7 41. Rc1 b3 42. Rb1 b2 43. Kg2 Bc5 44. Nc3 Ra3 45. Ne2 Rb3 46. Kf1 Ba3 47. Ke1 Rd3 48. Kf1 Rd2 {0-1 Ernst,S (2554)-Kollars,D (2592) Hamburg New Chess Brains 4th 2020 (3)}) 13... O-O (13... Qb6 $1 14. Nd2 O-O 15. Rfe1 Nh5 $1 $13) 14. Nxc6 (14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. Nxc6 Qd7 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 17. Nd2 Rfd8 $13) 14... bxc6 15. Qxa7 Bxc4 16. Rd1 c5 17. Bb7 Rc7 18. Bxc7 Qxc7 19. Na3 Be2 20. Re1 d3 0-1

