1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 (2... g6 {This is included to show an example of the note 11.a3} 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f4 O-O 6. Nf3 c5 7. d5 e6 8. Be2 exd5 9. cxd5 Re8 10. e5 dxe5 11. fxe5 Nfd7 12. O-O Nxe5 {White doesn't play d6 here because of Nbc6 and at some point Nd4, but instead plays Kh1, waits for Nbd7 and then d6} 13. Kh1 (13. d6 Nbc6) 13... Nbd7 14. d6) 3. Nf3 c5 4. g3 cxd4 5. Nxd4 d5 6. Bg2 e5 7. Nf3 d4 8. O-O Nc6 9. e3 Be7 10. exd4 exd4 11. Nbd2 (11. a3 {Here we should play either a5 or Be6} Be6 {[%cal Ge6c4]} 12. b3 Qd7 {In order to be able to play Rd8 to defend the d4 pawn} 13. Bb2 Rd8 {d3 may be too early as it would give the c3 square away and some ideas at some point with Nd5 cutting off the d3 pawn may exist later on. It reminds of a 4 pawns attack line with the same idea} 14. Nbd2 a5 {[%cal Ga5b4] To prevent b4 and soon d3 will be played. Passed pawns are meant to be pushed!} 15. Ne1 d3 {Not the only way to go, Bf5 or Bg4 were also possible. The d3 move can turn out to be a complete mess and should be calculated, but in general, it tends to work well!} 16. Rc1 O-O 17. Rc3 Ne5 18. f4 $19 {[%cal Ge7c5,Gd7d4,Ge5g4] many moves at Blacks disposal}) 11... Be6 12. Ng5 Bg4 13. Qb3 Qd7 14. Nde4 O-O 15. Qd3 Nxe4 16. Qxe4 Bf5 17. Qd5 Rad8 18. Bf4 h6 19. Ne4 g5 20. Bd2 Be6 21. Qb5 a6 22. Qb6 Bxc4 23. Rfc1 Bd5 24. h4 f6 25. Nc5 Bxc5 26. Bxd5+ Qxd5 27. Rxc5 Qf7 28. Rf1 Ne5 29. Rxe5 fxe5 30. Qxh6 gxh4 31. Qg5+ Qg7 32. Qxh4 Rfe8 33. f4 exf4 34. Rxf4 Rd6 35. Rg4 Rg6 36. Qh5 Ree6 37. Qd5 Qf6 38. Rf4 Qe5 39. Qd8+ Re8 40. Qd7 Rxg3+ {0-1 (40) Mastrovasilis,A (2510)-Edouard,R (2608) Cappelle la Grande 2010} 0-1

