1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. g3 cxd4 5. Nxd4 d5 6. Bg2 e5 7. Nf3 d4 8. O-O Nc6 9. e3 Be7 10. exd4 exd4 11. Bf4 Be6 $1 12. Ne5 Rc8 13. Re1 (13. Qa4 Qb6 $1 {With a fine game for Black} 14. Nd2 O-O 15. Rfe1 Nh5 $1 $13) 13... O-O 14. Nd2 (14. Nxc6 bxc6 15. Nd2 Qb6 $15 16. Nf3 Rfd8 17. Ne5 c5 18. b3 h6 19. Nd3 Bd6 20. Bxd6 Qxd6 $15) 14... Nxe5 15. Bxe5 Qd7 {[%cal Gf8d8,Gd4d3]} 16. Ne4 Rfd8 $1 {This move deserves an exclamation mark because it shows a very nice idea - Black is allowing the doubling of the f pawns and yet, Black will still be better after this.} (16... d3 {d3 is the best move}) 17. Bxf6 (17. Nxf6+ Bxf6 (17... gxf6 18. Bf4 Rxc4 $17) 18. Bxf6 gxf6 19. b3 d3 20. Qd2 b5 $1 $19 21. cxb5 Qxb5 22. Rad1 Rc2 23. Qe3 d2 24. Re2 (24. Rf1 Rxa2) 24... Rc1) 17... gxf6 18. Qh5 (18. b3 d3 (18... f5 19. Nd2 d3 (19... Bf6)) 19. Nc3 Bb4 20. Qd2 b5 $1 $19) 18... d3 19. Qh6 Qd4 20. b3 b5 (20... d2 $1 21. Red1 Bg4 $19) 21. c5 (21. cxb5 Rc2 $19) 21... Rxc5 $1 22. Nxc5 Bxc5 23. Rad1 (23. Rf1 d2 $19) 23... Qxf2+ 24. Kh1 Bf8 25. Qh5 Qc5 26. Qf3 d2 27. Rf1 Qg5 28. Qxf6 Qxf6 29. Rxf6 a5 30. Rf4 Bh6 31. Rh4 Kg7 32. Kg1 Bf5 33. Kf2 Bc2 34. Bf3 Rd6 35. Rg4+ Kf8 36. Re4 Rf6 0-1

